3) acceptance criteria coverage
- Application boot tree added: `Jidoka.Application` starts registry, session supervisor, attempt supervisor, bus, and `SessionServer`; coverage in `test/jidoka_session_server_test.exs` checks these processes are alive.
- `Jidoka.SessionServer` added as central durable writer: owns in-memory persistence adapter state in its own process and provides write APIs for session/run/attempt/lease persistence, plus snapshot generation.
- Public session lifecycle APIs added: open/resume/lookup/close via `Jidoka.Agent` and `Jidoka`, plus session/run snapshot access through `Jidoka.SessionServer` and facade methods in `Jidoka` (`snapshot_session`, `run_snapshot`).
- Resume behavior without durable ID change: test exercises open → persist entities → close → resume and asserts same session id plus rebuilt process (`pid` changes) with snapshot still present.
- Snapshot availability after restore: test validates session snapshot still contains persisted run and run snapshot contains persisted attempt/lease after resume.

4) blockers/assumptions
- Persistence is in-process (`Jidoka.Persistence.InMemory`) by design for this story phase, consistent with ST-MVP-002 and current dependencies.
- Full suite/tests beyond `mix precommit` were not run.
- `Jidoka.Agent` was introduced as a lightweight façade to preserve the existing public-facing pattern and route lifecycle calls through `SessionServer`, without implementing out-of-scope coding/verification flows.
